# Server TypeScript Conventions

## Stack

- TypeScript with strict mode, targeting ES2020/CommonJS
- Express for HTTP, Socket.IO for WebSocket events
- Mongoose for MongoDB, chess.js for move validation

## Patterns

- All game logic lives in `GameManager` â€” socket handlers are thin wrappers that delegate to it
- Socket event callbacks use the `(data, callback) => void` pattern for request/response
- Mongoose documents (`IRoom`) are the canonical type; use `serializeRoom()` before sending to clients
- Avoid naming Mongoose document fields that conflict with `Document` methods (e.g. use `timeIncrement` not `increment`)

## Testing

- Tests use Jest + ts-jest + mongodb-memory-server + real Socket.IO client/server pairs
- Shared helpers in `__tests__/setup.ts`: `setupDB`, `teardownDB`, `clearDB`
- Run with `npm test` (jest --forceExit --detectOpenHandles)

### Test structure

- `Room.test.ts` â€” Mongoose model: TTL index, schema validation, required fields, defaults, unique constraints
- `GameManager.test.ts` â€” Unit tests with mock sockets: room CRUD, color assignment, move validation, turn alternation, checkmate/draw detection, resign, reconnection (rejoin returns current state, timer restart, both players rejoin independently), timer/clock behavior, serialization
- `socket.test.ts` â€” Integration tests with real Socket.IO client/server: full createâ†’joinâ†’moveâ†’resign flow, reconnection (disconnect/rejoin/receive moves, timer events resume after rejoin, rejoin after game ends), move broadcast, Scholar's mate end-to-end

### Key rules

- Always call `gm.stopAllTimers()` in `afterEach` to prevent dangling intervals
- In socket tests, call `io.disconnectSockets(true)` in `afterEach` + small delay before `clearDB`
- To test a custom FEN position, update the DB then delete the in-memory chess instance: `(gm as any).games.delete(roomId)`
- Use `mockSocket()` for GameManager unit tests, real `socket.io-client` for integration tests
